<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="37">Status. Pontocaspian species, endemic to Caspian Sea Basin, Black Sea Basin, and Aral Sea Basin.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="37">Type locality. &quot;Australem oram caspii maris, Astrabadensem&quot; [southern coast of Caspian Sea, near Astrabad (= Gorgan, Iran)].</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="38">
<pageBreakToken pageId="7" pageNumber="38" start="start">Distribution</pageBreakToken>
. Black Sea Basin (also in Azov Sea and adjacent lower Don River), Caspian Sea Basin, and Aral Sea (including delta of Amu-Darya River). The Aral populations may have gone extinct in the 1980s (
<bibRefCitation author="Andreeva, SI" journalOrPublisher="Omskiy Gosudarstvennyy Pedagogicheskiy Universitet, Omsk" pageId="71" pageNumber="102" title="Evolyutsionnyye preobrazovaniya dvustvorchatykh mollyuskov Aral'skogo morya v usloviyakh ekologicheskogo krizisa." url="http://herba.msu.ru/shipunov/school/books/andreevy2003_evol_moll_aral.pdf" year="2003">Andreeva and Andreev 2003</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="38">
Taxonomic notes. The species has been subdivided into three geographical subspecies which were not recognised by 
<bibRefCitation author="Graf, DL" journalOrPublisher="Zoologicheskiy Zhurnal" pageId="75" pageNumber="106" url="http://www.mussel-project.net" year="2018">Graf and Cummings (2018)</bibRefCitation>
. It concerns a species with thin shells that yield very few diagnostic characters that show overlap. Here, we synonymise the subspecies pending molecular assessments of their status.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="conservation">
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="38">Conservation status. Not assessed.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
